Codification of objective variable.¶

We are going to understand, what is necessary to see receive a rating more or equal to 4. We choose stars as target variable. As we have checked before some of the closed restaurants also has this rating as well.

In order to use in classification model, we change this state to 1 or zeros.

In [6]:
restaurants['stars4'] = restaurants['stars'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x >= 4 else 0)

weekdays=['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
In [7]:
xtrain_4, xtest_4, ytrain_4, ytest_4 = train_test_split(restaurants.drop(columns=['stars4','stars']), 
                                                restaurants['stars4'],
                                                test_size=0.20,
                                                random_state=r, 
                                                stratify= restaurants['stars4'])

Since we had to manipulate variables more in details, we have processed already categorical variables. We do not need to encode again. We have now only numeric and boolean data. Booleans can be used in some of the machine learning algorithms. We will try in this way.

Scaling of Varibles¶

We have created a lot of variables. Probably some of them are quite corralated to each other or doesn't have a lot of importance. We cannot know without selection of the variables. I will here check first ridge and Lasso regression and later we will follow with PCA and LDA in order to stay with most used components.

We for sure require sccaling in order to process standardization for Ridge regression because the regularized variables require it.

In [8]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
model_scaled = scaler.fit(xtrain_4)
x4_train = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(xtrain_4), columns = xtrain_4.columns, index = xtrain_4.index)
x4_test = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(xtest_4), columns  = xtrain_4.columns, index = xtest_4.index)

2. Variable Selection¶

2.1.Ridge Regression¶

Ridge regression is linearilized version of regularization term l2. This forces learning algorithm to not only to fit the data but also keep the model weights as small as possible.

We will use SelectFromModel module of sklearn

In [9]:

Principal Component Analisis¶

We will apply PCA to reduced variables by following below steps. Since we have a lot of variables we would like to reduce dimension in this analisis.

1. Standardize the data: 
2. Compute the covariance matrix:
3. Compute the eigenvalues and eigenvectors: 
4. Sort the eigenvalues and eigenvectors: 
5. Project the data onto the lower-dimensional space:
In [20]:
pca = PCA(n_components=36)
#after trying without componenet 36 components fall under threshold

pca.fit(x4_train[selected_lasso])#according to Lasso selection
X_train_pca = pca.transform(x4_train[selected_lasso])
X_test_pca = pca.transform(x4_test[selected_lasso])
In [21]:
exp_var_pca = pca.explained_variance_ratio_# finding set of explained variances of the PCA components


cum_sum_eigenvalues = np.cumsum(exp_var_pca)# cumulative sum of explained variances

#graphing individual variances and cumulative variances.

threshold = 0.80
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6), dpi=80)
plt.bar(range(0,len(exp_var_pca)), exp_var_pca, alpha=0.5, align='center', label='Individual explained variance')
plt.step(range(0,len(cum_sum_eigenvalues)), cum_sum_eigenvalues, where='mid',label='Cumulative explained variance')
plt.axhline(y=threshold, color='r', linestyle='-')

plt.ylabel('Explained variance ratio')
plt.xlabel('Principal component index')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

LDA¶

LDA selection is similar to PCA but we use variance matrix instead of covariance matrix.

In [23]:
lda = LDA()# we are not fixing any number of the components.

lda.fit(x4_train, ytrain_4)
X_train_lda = lda.transform(x4_train)
X_test_lda = lda.transform(x4_test)
In [24]:
exp_var_lda = lda.explained_variance_ratio_
exp_var_lda

cum_sum_eigenvalues_lda = np.cumsum(exp_var_lda)# cumulative sum of explained variances
In [25]:
threshold = 0.80
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6), dpi=80)
plt.bar(range(0,len(exp_var_lda)), exp_var_lda, alpha=0.5, align='center', label='Individual explained variance', color='red')
plt.step(range(0,len(cum_sum_eigenvalues_lda)), cum_sum_eigenvalues_lda, where='mid',label='Cumulative explained variance')
plt.axhline(y=threshold, color='r', linestyle='-')

plt.ylabel('Explained variance ratio')
plt.xlabel('Principal component index')
plt.legend(loc='best')

This could be also because a good number of our variables are booleans.

In conclusion, we choose reducing number of variables with Lasso regression and reducing dimension by PCA, we will deploy the models with components we are left with.

Interpretability¶

We have some idea how is should be important some variables, here with help of library shap we will check importance of the variables also according to their values. Here we will analyze Ramdom Forest model.

In [50]:

%%time
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(clf_rf)

shap.summary_plot(shap_values[1],x4_test[selected_lasso])

No data for colormapping provided via 'c'. Parameters 'vmin', 'vmax' will be ignored

CPU times: user 6.97 s, sys: 1.41 s, total: 8.39 s
Wall time: 6.58 s

According to Shap Values of Random Forest model ,

  • Open restaurants likely to recieve more higher stars compared to closed ones.(No surprise)
  • Restaurants that give credit card availibility information doesn't likely to receive good valoration.
  • Review_count has more affect for highly valorated restaurants than lower reviews afecting negatively.
  • Restaurants with delivery affects negatively when it exist.
  • Ethnic restaurants doesn't have significant impact on star rate apart from Italian. Italian restaurants are disadvantaged on recieving high star rating.
  • Higher price range affects positively to receive higher rating. People are more likely to give review with high star if they are in a higher price_range2 restaurant
  • Elite users or Users with a lot of Yelp friends doesn't affect the model as expected.
  • Noise level, and group accepting restaurants less likely to receive high valoration.
